1. Create a 404.html Template
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Page Not Found - My Restaurant</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 50px;
            background-color: #fafafa;
        }
        h1 {
            font-size: 48px;
            color: #e74c3c;
        }
        p {
            font-size: 20px;
        }
        a {
            color: #007bff;
            text-decoration: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>404 - Page Not Found</h1>
    <p>Sorry, we couldn't find that page.</p>
    <p><a href="{% url 'home' %}">Return to Homepage</a></p>
</body>
</html>


2. Set DEBUG = False in settings.py
# settings.py
DEBUG = False

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ['*']  # or use your domain/IP in production


3. Serve Static Files Correctly in Production
# settings.py
# Ensure you have this:
STATICFILES_DIRS = [os.path.join(BASE_DIR, 'static')]
python manage.py collectstatic


4. Optional: Custom 404 View for Logging
# views.py
from django.shortcuts import render

def custom_404_view(request, exception):
    return render(request, '404.html', status=404)

#urls.py
# urls.py
handler404 = 'yourapp.views.custom_404_view'


5. Test It
http://localhost:8000/thispagedoesnotexist/

If DEBUG = False, you should see your custom 404 page.



